<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Discussion 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Rijksluchtvaartdienst (RLD), which is the airworthiness authority for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Netherlands, recently notified the FAA that an unsafe condition may exist on certain 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Fokker Model F28 Mark 0100 series airplanes. The RLD advises that operators have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reported several incidents in which the flight crew did not depress both halves of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
autopilot disconnect switch during the LAND 2 or LAND 3 approach and, as a result, one 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
autopilot remained engaged. Although certain aural warnings sounded and visual 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
indicators illuminated in these situations, the flight crew still believed that both autopilots 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
had been disconnected. Consequently, unanticipated movements of the stabilizer trim and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
higher than anticipated control forces of the flight controls occurred. Inadvertent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disconnection of only one autopilot when both autopilots are engaged could result in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unanticipated control surface movements. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Fokker has issued Service Bulletin SBF100&hyph;22&hyph;020, dated September 25, 1990, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that describes procedures for replacement of the autopilot disconnect switches with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
modified units. Installation of the modified units will ensure that if one-half of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
autopilot disconnect switch is depressed, both autopilots will disengage; in addition, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
system will remain separated. The RLD classified this service bulletin as mandatory and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
issued Netherlands Airworthiness Directive 90&hyph;112(A), dated October 15, 1990, in order 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to assure the continued airworthiness of these airplanes in the Netherlands. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This airplane model is manufactured in the Netherlands and is type certificated for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operation in the United States under the provisions of &sect;21.29 of the Federal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Aviation Regulations and the applicable bilateral airworthiness agreement. Pursuant to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this bilateral airworthiness agreement, the RLD has kept the FAA informed of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
situation described above. The FAA has examined the findings of the RLD, reviewed all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
available information, and determined that AD action is necessary for products of this type 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
design that are certificated for operation in the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Since an unsafe condition has been identified that is likely to exist or develop on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other airplanes of the same type design registered in the United States, the proposed AD 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would require replacement of the autopilot disconnect switches with modified units. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
actions would be required to be accomplished in accordance with the service bulletin 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
described previously. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The FAA estimates that 19 airplanes of U.S. registry would be affected by this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed AD, that it would take approximately 8 work hours per airplane to accomplish 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the proposed actions, and that the average labor rate is $55 per work hour. Required 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
parts would cost approximately $2,500 per airplane. Based on these figures, the total cost 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impact of the proposed AD on U.S. operators is estimated to be $55,860, or $2,940 per 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
airplane. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The total cost impact figure discussed above is based on assumptions that no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operator has yet accomplished any of the proposed requirements of this AD action, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that no operator would accomplish those actions in the future if this AD were not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
adopted. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The regulations proposed herein would not have substantial direct effects on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States, on the relationship between the national government and the States, or on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
distribution of power and responsibilities among the various levels of government. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Therefore, in accordance with Executive Order 12612, it is determined that this proposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would not have sufficient federalism implications to warrant the preparation of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Federalism Assessment.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For the reasons discussed above, I certify that this proposed regulation (1) is not a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``significant regulatory action'' under Executive Order 12866; (2) is not a ``significant rule'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the DOT Regulatory Policies and Procedures (44 FR 11034, February 26, 1979); 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and (3) if promulgated, will not have a significant economic impact, positive or negative, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on a substantial number of small entities under the criteria of the Regulatory Flexibility 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Act. A copy of the draft regulatory evaluation prepared for this action is contained in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
